            "body": "<p>There certainly is, at least in 3.5.<\/p>\n\n<p>Starting with something like this:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>switch(a.getType()){\n\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>All you need to do is click on the switch keyword and hit CTRL+1.  You should get a drop down which includes the option \"Add missing case statements\"<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 1967792,
            "question_id": 868261
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8a4d6f03a8879432d8563aefbf48e787?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 15903,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 34088,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/34088/aaron-digulla",
                "reputation": 330101,
                "display_name": "Aaron Digulla",
                "accept_rate": 77
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1242389705,
            "creation_date": 1242389705,
            "body": "<p>The content assists in Eclipse 3.4 will help you write the code. Just type <code>case<\/code> and press Ctrl+Space and you'll get a list of unused enums.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 868338,
